---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why has my Officer paver driveway settled at the edges?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "If you've got pavers that have walked outwards or settled 20-30mm at the edge by year 2-3, the install almost certainly didn't have proper edge restraint — or had a token plastic strip pinned with timber pegs that gave up under load. Pavers are a flexible system: every vehicle pass pushes the outer paver outward by a tiny amount. Without an edge restraint to push back, the outer pavers walk, the bedding sand washes out from underneath, and the surrounding pavers start to settle in turn. The fix is a concrete haunch (preferred) or driven steel edge along the entire perimeter. Retrofitting edge restraint to an already-settled driveway means lifting the outer 600mm of pavers, building the haunch, re-laying — typically $80-$120/lm." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What's the standard concrete haunch detail for Officer paver driveways?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Our standard concrete haunch is a 150mm wide × 200mm deep continuous concrete strip running the full perimeter of the paved area, poured in 25 MPa concrete, with the top of the haunch flush with the underside of the paver bedding. The haunch sits BELOW finished surface level — invisible once the pavers are laid and surrounding ground is reinstated. It locks the outer pavers in place permanently. Saw-cut articulation joints in the haunch at 3-4m centres mirror the AS 2870 joint requirements for slab-on-ground work over reactive clay. The haunch is poured before pavers are laid, not after — pouring against an already-laid edge doesn't bond properly." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When does steel edging make more sense than concrete haunch in Officer?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "We use 5mm hot-dip galvanised steel edging (typically 100mm or 150mm deep) on lighter-traffic paving — patios, pool surrounds, garden paths — where there's no vehicle load and we want a tighter sightline against turf or garden bed. Steel edging is faster to install ($25-$45/lm vs $55-$90/lm for concrete haunch) and gives a cleaner finish line. We won't use it on driveways or anywhere with vehicle load — the pegs eventually fatigue and the system loses its restraint. Steel edging is also our go-to where we're paving against existing landscaping and minimising disturbance matters." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What about polymer sand for joints — does it act as edge restraint?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "No — polymer-sand jointing is essential for joint stability and stops weed germination and joint-sand washout, but it's NOT a substitute for edge restraint. Polymer sand locks adjacent pavers together so they move as a mass; edge restraint stops that mass from migrating sideways. You need both. We use a top-tier polymer-modified jointing sand (Techniseal HP NextGel or equivalent), swept in dry, watered to activate the polymer, allowed to cure 24-48 hours. It lasts 5-10 years before needing top-up — significantly longer than plain washed sand which washes out within 1-2 winters in Officer." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does your warranty change with and without proper edge restraint?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Standard Officer Paving Co workmanship warranty on a paved driveway is 24 months with a properly engineered concrete-haunch edge restraint installed. That warranty covers settlement, joint integrity, paver alignment and edge stability. If a client specifically asks us to install pavers without a concrete haunch — usually to save on install cost — we reduce the workmanship warranty to 12 months on alignment and explicitly exclude edge migration from cover. We document this in writing on the quote. Most clients pick the longer-warranty option after seeing the cost differential ($1,200-$2,500 extra haunch cost vs $4,000-$7,000 to retrofit it later when the driveway has settled)." }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Paver edge restraint in Officer — why driveways settle | (03) 9003 0108"
  description="Edge restraint for paver driveways in Officer 3809. Concrete haunch vs steel edging, polymer-sand jointing, retrofit costs, warranty difference. Stop pavers settling at year 2."
  canonical="https://officerpavingco.com.au/edge-restraint-officer/">
  <Fragment slot="head">
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />
  </Fragment>

  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-inner">
      <span class="hero-eyebrow">Edge Restraint &middot; Paver Driveways &middot; Officer 3809</span>
      <h1>Edge restraint in <span class="accent">Officer</span> — the detail that decides whether your pavers last 5 years or 30.</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        If you&rsquo;ve looked at a 5-year-old paver driveway in Officer
        South or older Heritage Springs and noticed the outer rows have
        walked outwards, sunk by 20&ndash;30mm at the corners, or the
        joint sand is gone — you&rsquo;re looking at a missing or failed
        edge restraint. It&rsquo;s the invisible 5% of the job that
        determines the visible 95% of the result.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
        <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/quote/">Book a free site visit</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Why pavers move</span>
      <h2>The settlement story in 60 seconds.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Pavers are a deliberately flexible system — that&rsquo;s their
          advantage on reactive clay. Each unit settles independently,
          tolerating clay movement that would crack a slab. But that
          same flexibility means every vehicle pass over a paver
          driveway pushes the outermost paver outward by a tiny,
          imperceptible amount.
        </p>

        <p>
          Without something pushing back along the perimeter, those
          micro-movements accumulate. By year 2 the outer paver has
          walked outward 2&ndash;5mm. By year 3 it&rsquo;s 8&ndash;15mm.
          The bedding sand starts washing out from the gap. The next
          paver in starts settling into the void. Within 5 years the
          outer 600mm of the driveway looks tired, sunken, the joint
          sand is gone, and the cure is to lift everything, build proper
          edge restraint, and re-lay.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What edge restraint does.</h3>
        <p>
          A continuous concrete haunch or driven steel edge along the
          paved perimeter physically prevents the outer paver from
          migrating. It locks the entire paved surface against itself.
          With proper restraint, paver driveways in Officer routinely
          hit 25&ndash;40 years before the bedding course needs
          attention. Without it, they look tired by year 5.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Concrete haunch</span>
      <h2>The driveway-grade detail.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Our standard concrete haunch for an Officer paver driveway is a
          <strong>150mm wide &times; 200mm deep continuous concrete strip</strong>
          poured around the full perimeter in 25 MPa concrete. The top of
          the haunch sits flush with the underside of the paver bedding
          sand — so it&rsquo;s completely invisible once pavers are laid
          and surrounding ground is reinstated.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">How we build it.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Excavate the perimeter trench to design depth (typically 250mm below finished surface to allow paver thickness + bedding sand + haunch).</li>
          <li>Compact subgrade to AS 3727 spec — same as the main pavement base.</li>
          <li>Pour 25 MPa concrete monolithically against compacted ground (no separate formwork inside if the trench is clean).</li>
          <li>Saw-cut articulation joints at 3&ndash;4m centres per AS 2870 reactive-clay requirements — same logic as a slab.</li>
          <li>Cure 7 days minimum before laying bedding sand and pavers against the haunch.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why it has to be poured first.</h3>
        <p>
          A common shortcut is laying the pavers, then trying to pour
          concrete against the laid edge afterwards. It doesn&rsquo;t
          bond properly — the haunch and the pavers move independently
          from day one, the haunch starts cracking away from the paver
          edge by year 2, and the restraint function is compromised.
          Haunch first, pavers second. Always.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Cost.</h3>
        <p>
          A concrete haunch adds typically $55&ndash;$90 per linear metre
          to a paving install. On a 60sqm Officer driveway with ~32 linear
          metres of perimeter, that&rsquo;s an additional $1,800&ndash;$2,900
          to the total project cost. Retrofitting the same haunch to a
          driveway that&rsquo;s already settled and needs lifting first
          runs $4,000&ndash;$7,000 — the maths of doing it once,
          properly, is pretty clear.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Steel edging</span>
      <h2>When the lighter detail is right.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          On Officer patios, pool surrounds, garden paths and other
          non-vehicle paved areas, we use <strong>5mm hot-dip galvanised
          steel edging</strong> driven into the prepared base. The
          standard product is 100mm or 150mm deep, with integrated stake
          pockets driven every 600mm with 400&ndash;500mm steel pegs.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why steel here.</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Faster install — $25&ndash;$45 per linear metre vs $55&ndash;$90/lm for concrete haunch.</li>
          <li>Cleaner sightline against turf or garden bed — the steel sits flush with finished levels.</li>
          <li>Galvanised finish lasts 30+ years in residential soil conditions.</li>
          <li>Less site disturbance when paving against existing established landscaping.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Where we won&rsquo;t use steel.</h3>
        <p>
          Anywhere a vehicle drives. Steel edging eventually fatigues
          under repeated vehicle loading — the pegs flex, the bedding
          base compacts asymmetrically, and within 10 years the
          restraint function is gone. Driveways and crossovers always
          get a concrete haunch in our spec. No exceptions, no
          &ldquo;we&rsquo;ll save you a few hundred dollars&rdquo;
          variations.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section section-alt">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <span class="section-eyebrow">Polymer-sand jointing</span>
      <h2>The other half of paver longevity.</h2>
      <div class="divider"></div>
      <div style="max-width: 65rem;">
        <p>
          Edge restraint locks the perimeter. Polymer-sand jointing
          locks the interior. Together they turn a flexible paver
          system into a coherent, durable, low-maintenance surface that
          tolerates Officer&rsquo;s Class H clay movement without
          falling apart.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">What we use.</h3>
        <p>
          A polymer-modified jointing sand — Techniseal HP NextGel or
          equivalent product certified for vehicular paver applications.
          Swept dry into the joints, compacted, second pass to top up,
          watered carefully to activate the polymer binder, allowed to
          cure 24&ndash;48 hours before traffic.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Lifespan vs plain sand.</h3>
        <p>
          Plain washed sand jointing in Officer washes out within
          1&ndash;2 winters — every heavy rain event flushes a percentage
          of joint sand into the stormwater system, weeds germinate in
          the gaps, joints widen, individual pavers start rocking.
          Polymer sand resists wash-out and weed germination, lasting
          5&ndash;10 years before a refresh is needed. Refresh cost is
          modest — typically $400&ndash;$900 on a residential driveway
          depending on area.
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 2rem;">Why both matter.</h3>
        <p>
          Polymer sand without edge restraint: the jointed mass migrates
          outwards as a unit, the edge collapses, joints fail in
          rotation. Edge restraint without polymer sand: joints wash
          out, weeds invade, individual pavers rock. Both done properly:
          driveway looks new at year 15. That&rsquo;s what our 24-month
          workmanship warranty is staked on.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-inner">
      <div class="cta-block">
        <h2>Free Officer paving quote — restraint included.</h2>
        <p>
          Every paving quote we issue itemises the edge restraint
          separately so you can see exactly what&rsquo;s being installed
          and why. No mystery line-items, no missing details.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" style="justify-content:center;">
          <a class="btn btn-primary" href="tel:+61390030108">&#9742; Call (03) 9003 0108</a>
          <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="mailto:quotes@officerpavingco.com.au">Email quotes@officerpavingco.com.au</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
